          {
            "commit": "bd455e64765305f77ca394c2004ea8d0203881c6",
            "subject": "LU-4952 osd: wrong paramters for dmu_tx_hold_write"
          }
        ],
        "author": {
          "name": "Chris Horn",
          "email": "hornc@cray.com",
          "date": "2014-02-03 21:24:01.000000000",
          "tz": -360
        },
        "committer": {
          "name": "Oleg Drokin",
          "email": "oleg.drokin@intel.com",
          "date": "2014-05-16 19:54:49.000000000",
          "tz": -240
        },
        "subject": "LU-4578 ptlrpc: Early replies need to honor at_max",
        "message": "LU-4578 ptlrpc: Early replies need to honor at_max\n\nWhen determining whether an early reply can be sent the server will\ncalculate the new deadline based on an offset from the request\narrival time. However, when actually setting the new deadline\nthe server offsets the current time. This can result in deadlines\nbeing extended more than at_max seconds past the request arrival\ntime. Instead, the server should offset the arrival time when updating\nits request timeout.\n\nWhen a client receives an early reply it doesn't know the server side\narrival time so we use the original sent time as an approximation.\n\nSigned-off-by: Chris Horn <hornc@cray.com>\nChange-Id: I1b7b04bd20ea5d471ab3777f987e89add744b813\nReviewed-on: http://review.whamcloud.com/9100\nTested-by: Jenkins\nReviewed-by: James Simmons <uja.ornl@gmail.com>\nTested-by: Maloo <hpdd-maloo@intel.com>\nReviewed-by: Christopher J. Morrone <chris.morrone.llnl@gmail.com>\nReviewed-by: Oleg Drokin <oleg.drokin@intel.com>\n"
      },
      "branch": "refs/heads/b2_5"
    }
  },
